 This means a Gemini-parent → `"small"` child never 404s asking for `"haiku"`. Literal model names (`claude-haiku-4-5`, `gemini-2.5-flash`, …) are still accepted for backwards compatibility. See [docs/wiki/Multi-Agent.md](docs/wiki/Multi-Agent.md) and [ADR-012](docs/adrs/ADR-012-multi-agent.md). Coordinator mode (`duh --coordinator`) turns the main agent into a pure orchestrator that delegates everything to subagents.
 
+## Double-agent TDD
+
+D.U.H. also has a first-class **double-agent TDD** flow built on the same child-agent infrastructure. The `duh tdd` subcommand runs a strict six-phase loop:
+
+1. Navigator drafts the test spec.
+2. Driver writes the failing test and D.U.H. runs the test command to prove RED.
+3. Driver writes the minimum code to pass.
+4. Navigator proposes a refactor.
+5. Driver applies the refactor.
+6. Navigator validates that the refactor landed cleanly and tests still pass.
+
+If the RED step passes unexpectedly, D.U.H. sends the result back to the Navigator, tightens the spec, and retries RED before moving on.
+
+```bash
+duh tdd "add CSV export for invoices" \
+  --test-command "pytest tests/test_invoices.py -q" \
+  --driver-model inherit \
+  --navigator-model inherit
+```
+
+Use this when you want D.U.H. to enforce the red-green-refactor discipline explicitly instead of relying on a generic implementation prompt. See [docs/wiki/Double-Agent-TDD.md](docs/wiki/Double-Agent-TDD.md) and [ADR-076](docs/adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd.md).
+
 ## Security
 
 D.U.H. ships a three-layer pluggable security module (ADR-053 + ADR-054) that addresses every published agent RCE in the 2024-2026 CVE corpus:
diff --git a/docs/adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd.md b/docs/adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000..e2e0064546c5f2e304126123e739cfe80f7ca910
--- /dev/null
+++ b/docs/adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd.md
@@ -0,0 +1,134 @@
+# ADR-076: Double-Agent TDD Flow
+
+## Status
+
+Accepted
+
+## Context
+
+D.U.H. already supports subagents, coordinator-style orchestration, and
+shared session/tool wiring. What it does not provide is a first-class way to
+run a disciplined red-green-refactor loop with explicit separation between a
+test-writing Driver and a reviewing Navigator.
+
+The requested flow has two hard requirements:
+
+1. The six phases must execute in strict order.
+2. The RED phase must be validated by running tests and proving the new test
+   fails before any production change is attempted.
+
+This needs to be a real feature users can trigger, not just a prompt recipe,
+and it should reuse existing D.U.H. abstractions instead of creating a
+separate agent runtime.
+
+## Decision
+
+Add a reusable orchestration module that runs a **double-agent TDD session**
+using existing child-agent infrastructure from `duh.agents.run_agent` and the
+shared dependency/tool wiring from `SessionBuilder`.
+
+The user-facing entry point will be a new `duh tdd` subcommand. The command
+will accept:
+
+- A task description.
+- A required `--test-command` used to validate RED and GREEN/validation.
+- Optional model/turn controls for the child agents.
+
+The orchestrator will run the following ordered phases:
+
+1. `navigator_spec`
+2. `driver_red`
+3. `driver_green`
+4. `navigator_refactor`
+5. `driver_refactor`
+6. `navigator_validate`
+
+Each phase emits a structured result containing:
+
+- phase name
+- agent role
+- prompt/response text
+- optional test-command execution result
+- status (`ok`, `needs_revision`, or `error`)
+
+### RED contract
+
+After `driver_red`, D.U.H. runs the supplied test command in the workspace.
+
+- If the command exits non-zero, RED is considered valid and the failure text
+  is recorded as a **red failure**.
+- If the command exits zero, the Navigator must revise the test spec and the
+  flow retries the RED phase up to a bounded retry count.
+
+RED failure output is preserved separately from GREEN/validation success so
+the user and tests can assert that the flow genuinely went through RED before
+GREEN.
+
+### Driver/Navigator contract
+
+Navigator responsibilities:
+
+- Draft the initial test spec.
+- Revise the spec if RED passes unexpectedly.
+- Propose a refactor after GREEN.
+- Validate that the refactor was applied and tests still pass.
+
+Driver responsibilities:
+
+- Implement the failing test from the current Navigator spec.
+- Implement the minimum code to make the test command pass.
+- Apply the Navigator’s refactor proposal.
+
+The Navigator never edits code directly in this flow; it reviews and steers.
+The Driver is the only role instructed to change the codebase.
+
+## Alternatives Considered
+
+### 1. Prompt-only recipe in README
+
+Rejected. That would not provide a real product surface, strict phase
+tracking, or testable guarantees about RED/GREEN sequencing.
+
+### 2. Implement as a Swarm/parallel workflow
+
+Rejected. The required contract is intentionally serial. `SwarmTool` is useful
+for independent parallel subtasks, but RED/GREEN/REFACTOR has strict causal
+dependencies between phases.
+
+### 3. Add only a slash command
+
+Rejected. A top-level subcommand is easier to test end-to-end and gives clear
+`--help` output. A slash command can be added later on top of the same
+orchestrator if needed.
+
+### 4. Build a new bespoke agent runtime
+
+Rejected. D.U.H. already has `run_agent`, `Engine`, `Deps`, `SessionBuilder`,
+and tool patching for child agents. Reusing those keeps provider behavior,
+tool access, and permissions consistent.
+
+## Consequences
+
+### Positive
+
+- The feature is testable with the stub provider and mocked child-agent runs.
+- RED/GREEN/REFACTOR becomes explicit state, not implicit prompt behavior.
+- Child agents inherit the same provider/tool environment as the parent
+  session, preserving existing abstractions.
+
+### Negative
+
+- The workflow depends on a user-supplied test command; D.U.H. cannot infer
+  the correct test invocation reliably for every repository.
+- The Navigator revision loop adds orchestration complexity and needs bounded
+  retries to avoid infinite loops.
+
+## Implementation Notes
+
+- Put the orchestration logic in a dedicated module so CLI/tests can call it
+  directly.
+- Keep test execution outside the child agents by using the already-wired
+  executor from the parent session. This makes RED/GREEN checks deterministic
+  and observable by the orchestrator.
+- Update README, wiki, parser help, and command handling together so the
+  feature is discoverable from both docs and `--help`.
